# Creative Prisim – Cursor Operational Rules
# The Intelligence of Seeing (IoS) — Phase 2
# Version 1.0

---

## 1. PROJECT IDENTITY

This folder contains the Creative Prisim prototype — a structured reasoning
environment in which multiple AI roles collaborate to help a person explore
problems, generate ideas, and evaluate solutions.

It is NOT:
- a production application
- an autonomous agent system
- a chatbot
- a general-purpose AI tool

It IS:
- a human-centered cognitive studio
- a modular, role-based reasoning prototype
- an experimental system under active iterative development
- a portfolio project documenting learning through construction

Cursor must treat this codebase as a design prototype in active iteration.
Clarity, inspectability, and modularity are the primary engineering values.


---

## 2. CONCEPTUAL AUTHORITY

The Creative Prisim architecture is governed by the following documents,
located in Creative Prisim System Prompts/:

- system_constitution_v2.docx     → philosophical foundation
- system_laws.docx                → ten core operating principles
- operating_protocol_v2.docx      → nine-stage workflow
- blackboard_data_model_v1.docx   → state schema
- studio_run_schema_v2.1.docx     → session JSON structure
- traits_matrix_weighting.docx    → personality modulation layer
- director_evaluation_protocol    → Director review criteria
- discovery_framework_v2.docx     → Discovery phase protocol

Cursor may reference these documents for terminology and design intent.

Cursor must NOT:
- reinterpret core architecture without explicit user instruction
- redesign role responsibilities
- rename core roles (Director, Creator, Critic, Researcher, Scribe)
- alter the Blackboard schema without explicit versioning


---

## 3. CORE ROLES — DO NOT RENAME OR REDEFINE

The system operates through five named roles. These names are fixed.

  Director    — orchestrates process, communicates with user
  Creator     — generates ideas, expands possibility space
  Critic      — evaluates and refines ideas constructively
  Researcher  — introduces contextual knowledge and precedents
  Scribe      — records all reasoning artifacts to the Blackboard

Each role is instantiated via the prompt compiler (build_prompt).
Role behavior is shaped by trait weights, not hardcoded instructions.


---

## 4. FILE STRUCTURE

creative_prisim/
  creative_prisim_phase0.ipynb    ← foundation scaffold
  creative_prisim_phase1.ipynb    ← full workflow (when built)
  sessions/                       ← JSON session records (auto-created)
  .env                            ← API key (never committed)
  .cursorrules                    ← this file

Rules:
- Session outputs always write to sessions/
- Use pathlib for all file paths
- Use relative paths only
- Never hardcode absolute paths


---

## 5. SCHEMA DISCIPLINE

The Blackboard state object is defined in creative_prisim_phase0.ipynb
(create_blackboard function) and governed by studio_run_schema_v2.1.

Cursor must NOT:
- rename Blackboard keys
- flatten nested structures
- remove fields from the schema
- silently add new fields

Schema changes require explicit user approval and version notation.
If output violates schema: stop, report violation, await instruction.


---

## 6. PROMPT COMPILER INTEGRITY

Role prompts are generated by build_prompt(role, weights, context, mode).

Cursor must NOT:
- hardcode role prompts outside the compiler
- bypass the traits system
- modify trait threshold values without explicit instruction
- add new trait dimensions without discussion

The traits system is the control surface for role behavior.
Changes to weights are experiments — document them in LOGBOOK.md.


---

## 7. SINGLE-VARIABLE DISCIPLINE

The Creative Prisim follows iterative experimental methodology.

When testing behavior changes, modify ONE variable at a time:
- a single trait weight
- a single role prompt
- the global mode
- the model selection

Before any change, Cursor must state:
  Variable being modified: ______
  Expected effect: ______
  How to verify: ______


---

## 8. HUMAN-IN-THE-LOOP IS NON-NEGOTIABLE

The Person in the Loop retains authority at every stage.

Cursor must NEVER:
- automate across user decision points
- simulate user responses
- remove input() or feedback prompts
- create autonomous loops that run without user checkpoints

The system waits for the human. Always.


---

## 9. ITERATIVE DEVELOPMENT PROTOCOL

This project is under active iterative construction.
The architecture will evolve. That is expected and correct.

Cursor should:
- prefer small, testable changes
- make logic explicit and readable
- flag when a change affects multiple components
- suggest rather than silently refactor

Cursor must NOT:
- introduce frameworks or dependencies without discussion
- refactor working code without explicit request
- optimize for performance at the cost of readability
- introduce abstractions that obscure the reasoning structure


---

## 10. SIMPLICITY PRINCIPLE

This is a cognitive instrument, not a software product.

Prefer:
- clear functions over clever abstractions
- explicit logic over implicit magic
- readable code over optimized code
- flat structure over deep nesting

The code should be as readable as the documentation.


---

## 11. FAILURE PROTOCOL

If any runtime failure occurs:

1. Stop execution
2. Report the exact error and location
3. Do NOT apply speculative fixes
4. Await explicit user instruction


---

## 12. LOGBOOK DISCIPLINE

All experiments, observations, and significant changes should be noted
in LOGBOOK.md (to be created in this folder).

Format:
  [DATE] — what was tested, what was observed, what changed, what's next.

The Logbook is the experimental record. Keep it current.


---

## 13. PROTECTIVE HEADER

All engine files should include:

# Creative Prisim – Experimental Prototype
# The Intelligence of Seeing (IoS) — Do Not Refactor Without Explicit Approval


---

## 14. RELATIONSHIP TO PARENT PROJECT

This folder is a subfolder of the_intelligence_of_seeing/.
The G-S-A-C experiments at the root level are the conceptual predecessors
of this work. They share the same philosophical DNA.

The root .cursorrules governs G-S-A-C work.
This .cursorrules governs Creative Prisim work.
They do not conflict — they govern different phases of the same project.

The creative lineage is continuous. The rules are scoped.

---

End of Creative Prisim Cursor Operational Rules
